    topicIntroduction: {
        overview: "Atomic structure is the foundational framework of all chemistry. Every chemical property — reactivity, bonding, periodicity, spectroscopy — is ultimately rooted in how protons, neutrons, and electrons are arranged within atoms. Understanding atomic structure means understanding why elements behave as they do: why sodium is reactive, why carbon forms four bonds, why noble gases are inert, and why the periodic table is arranged as it is.",
        whyItMatters: "Modern technology depends entirely on precise knowledge of atomic structure. Semiconductors, MRI scanners, nuclear power, mass spectrometry in drug testing, radioisotopes in cancer treatment — all rely on manipulating atomic properties. The electronic configuration of an atom determines which bonds it forms, which reactions it undergoes, and what its compounds look like. Without atomic structure, there is no chemistry.",
        bigPicture: "Atoms are not indivisible — they contain a dense, positive nucleus (protons and neutrons) surrounded by a much larger region occupied by electrons. Electrons do not orbit randomly; they occupy specific energy levels (shells), each divided into subshells (s, p, d, f), each containing orbitals with defined shapes. The number and arrangement of electrons determine an element's chemical identity. Removing electrons (ionisation) requires energy that can be measured precisely — and successive ionisation energies provide direct experimental evidence for the shell model.",
        priorKnowledge: [
            "Basic atomic theory: atoms are the smallest unit of an element",
            "Elements and the periodic table: atomic number, mass number",
            "States of matter and the concept of charge",
            "Energy: the idea that processes require or release energy",
            "Basic mathematics: logarithms (for ionisation energy graphs), ratios (for isotope abundance calculations)"
        ],
        topicRoadmap: [
            "Subatomic particles: protons, neutrons, electrons — mass, charge, location",
            "Atomic number, mass number, and their relationship to particle numbers",
            "Isotopes: definition, notation, and natural abundance",
            "Relative atomic mass: calculating Ar from isotope data",
            "Mass spectrometry: how it works and how it identifies isotopes and molecules",
            "Shell model: principal quantum number and electron capacity of shells",
            "Subshells and orbitals: s, p, d, f — shapes, capacities, and energy ordering",
            "Electronic configuration: writing full and abbreviated configurations",
            "Aufbau principle, Pauli exclusion principle, Hund's rule",
            "Ionisation energy: definition, successive IEs, and evidence for shell structure",
            "Trends in first ionisation energy across periods and down groups",
            "Shielding and effective nuclear charge"
        ]
    },

    concepts: [
        "Atoms contain protons and neutrons in a central nucleus, with electrons occupying shells around the nucleus",
        "Atomic number (Z) equals the number of protons; mass number (A) equals protons plus neutrons",
        "Isotopes are atoms of the same element with the same proton number but different neutron numbers",
        "Relative atomic mass is the weighted mean mass of an atom of an element relative to 1/12 the mass of carbon-12",
        "Electrons occupy shells, subshells, and orbitals in order of increasing energy",
        "The electronic configuration of an atom determines its chemical properties and position in the periodic table",
        "Ionisation energy is the energy required to remove one mole of electrons from one mole of gaseous atoms",
        "Successive ionisation energies provide experimental evidence for the existence of electron shells",
        "Shielding by inner electrons reduces the effective nuclear charge experienced by outer electrons",
        "First ionisation energy increases across a period (with exceptions) and decreases down a group"
    ],

    theory: "Atoms consist of a positively charged nucleus containing protons and neutrons, surrounded by negatively charged electrons. The chemical behaviour of an element is determined by its electron arrangement. Electrons occupy discrete energy levels — shells — each subdivided into subshells (s, p, d, f) containing orbitals. Orbitals are filled in order of increasing energy following the Aufbau principle, with the constraint that each orbital holds at most two electrons of opposite spin (Pauli exclusion principle) and that degenerate orbitals are occupied singly before pairing occurs (Hund's rule). The energy required to remove electrons — ionisation energy — varies systematically with nuclear charge, shielding, and distance from the nucleus, providing quantitative experimental evidence for this shell model.",

    keyDefinitions: {
        "Atomic Number (Z)":           "The number of protons in the nucleus of an atom; defines the element",
        "Mass Number (A)":             "The total number of protons and neutrons (nucleons) in the nucleus",
        "Nucleon":                     "A particle found in the nucleus — either a proton or a neutron",
        "Isotopes":                    "Atoms of the same element (same proton number) with different numbers of neutrons (different mass numbers)",
        "Relative Atomic Mass (Ar)":   "The weighted mean mass of an atom of an element relative to 1/12 the mass of a ¹²C atom",
        "Relative Isotopic Mass":      "The mass of one atom of an isotope relative to 1/12 the mass of a ¹²C atom",
        "Shell":                       "A principal energy level occupied by electrons; numbered 1, 2, 3... from the nucleus outward",
        "Subshell":                    "A subdivision of a shell; types are s, p, d, f — each contains a specific number of orbitals",
        "Orbital":                     "A region of space that can hold a maximum of two electrons with opposite spins; defined by a specific energy and shape",
        "Electronic Configuration":    "A notation describing the number of electrons in each subshell of an atom or ion",
        "Ionisation Energy (IE)":      "The energy required to remove one mole of electrons from one mole of gaseous atoms or ions: X(g) → X⁺(g) + e⁻",
        "First Ionisation Energy":     "Energy to remove the first (most easily removed) electron from a gaseous atom",
        "Successive Ionisation Energies": "The energies to remove the 1st, 2nd, 3rd... electrons in sequence from a gaseous atom",
        "Shielding":                   "The reduction in effective nuclear charge experienced by an outer electron due to repulsion from inner electrons",
        "Effective Nuclear Charge":    "The net nuclear charge experienced by a particular electron, accounting for shielding by inner electrons",
        "Aufbau Principle":            "Electrons fill orbitals in order of increasing energy — lowest energy orbitals filled first",
        "Pauli Exclusion Principle":   "No two electrons in an atom can have the same set of four quantum numbers; each orbital holds at most two electrons of opposite spin",
        "Hund's Rule":                 "In degenerate (equal energy) orbitals, electrons occupy them singly before pairing; all singly occupied orbitals have the same spin",
        "Mass Spectrometry":           "An analytical technique that separates ions by their mass-to-charge ratio (m/z) to determine isotopic composition and relative atomic mass"
    },

