    topicIntroduction: {
        overview: "Dynamic equilibrium describes the state reached by a reversible reaction in a closed system when the forward and reverse reactions proceed at equal rates, resulting in constant macroscopic concentrations of all species. Far from being static, equilibrium is a continuously active, dynamic balance — molecules are constantly reacting in both directions, but their concentrations no longer change. Understanding equilibrium is essential for predicting how chemical systems respond to disturbance and for designing industrial processes that maximise efficiency.",
        whyItMatters: "Virtually every important chemical process — from the synthesis of ammonia in the Haber process that feeds half the world's population, to the oxygen-carrying capacity of haemoglobin, to the buffering of blood pH — is governed by equilibrium principles. Le Chatelier's principle and the equilibrium constant are the two most powerful predictive tools in all of physical chemistry. Without them, neither the pharmaceutical industry nor the petrochemical industry could operate efficiently.",
        bigPicture: "A reversible reaction does not go to completion — it reaches a point where the tendency to react forward equals the tendency to react backward. The position of this balance (expressed as Kc) is fixed by temperature alone. Other factors — concentration, pressure, catalysts — shift the position of equilibrium or affect the rate at which equilibrium is reached, but only temperature changes Kc itself. This distinction between shifting equilibrium position and changing Kc is the conceptual heart of the topic.",
        priorKnowledge: [
            "Reversible reactions and the use of ⇌ in equations",
            "Rates of reaction: collision theory, activation energy, and factors affecting rate",
            "Concentration: moles per unit volume (mol dm⁻³)",
            "Basic thermodynamics: exothermic and endothermic reactions, enthalpy change ΔH",
            "Mole calculations and stoichiometry"
        ],
        topicRoadmap: [
            "Reversible reactions and the closed system requirement for equilibrium",
            "Dynamic equilibrium: equal forward and reverse rates, constant concentrations",
            "The equilibrium position: products favoured (Kc >> 1) vs reactants favoured (Kc << 1)",
            "Le Chatelier's principle: concentration changes, pressure changes, temperature changes",
            "The effect of catalysts on equilibrium",
            "The equilibrium constant expression Kc: writing expressions from equations",
            "Calculating Kc from equilibrium concentrations",
            "Predicting the effect of temperature on Kc for exothermic and endothermic reactions",
            "The Haber process: industrial application of equilibrium principles",
            "The Contact process: SO₂ oxidation and compromise conditions"
        ]
    },

    concepts: [
        "A reversible reaction in a closed system reaches dynamic equilibrium when forward and reverse rates are equal",
        "At equilibrium, macroscopic properties (concentration, colour, pressure) are constant but microscopic reactions continue",
        "The equilibrium position describes whether products or reactants are favoured",
        "Le Chatelier's principle: a system at equilibrium subjected to a change will respond to oppose that change",
        "Increasing concentration of a reactant shifts equilibrium to the right; removing a product shifts equilibrium to the right",
        "For reactions involving gases, increasing pressure shifts equilibrium toward the side with fewer moles of gas",
        "Increasing temperature shifts equilibrium in the endothermic direction; decreasing temperature shifts it in the exothermic direction",
        "A catalyst increases the rate of both forward and reverse reactions equally — it does not shift the equilibrium position but reduces the time taken to reach equilibrium",
        "Kc is the equilibrium constant in terms of concentration; its value depends only on temperature",
        "A large Kc (>> 1) means products are favoured; a small Kc (<< 1) means reactants are favoured"
    ],

    theory: "A reversible reaction in a closed system reaches dynamic equilibrium when the rate of the forward reaction equals the rate of the reverse reaction. At this point, concentrations of all species remain constant — not because reaction has stopped, but because every molecule converted forward is simultaneously replaced by the reverse reaction. The position of equilibrium (quantified by Kc) is an intrinsic property of the reaction at a given temperature. External perturbations (concentration, pressure) shift the position without altering Kc; only a temperature change alters Kc itself. This distinction is the foundation of all industrial equilibrium optimisation.",

    keyDefinitions: {
        "Reversible Reaction":       "A reaction that can proceed in both the forward and reverse directions, denoted by ⇌",
        "Closed System":             "A system that exchanges energy but not matter with its surroundings — essential for equilibrium to be established",
        "Dynamic Equilibrium":       "The state in a reversible reaction where the forward rate equals the reverse rate, and macroscopic concentrations remain constant while microscopic reactions continue",
        "Equilibrium Position":      "A qualitative description of whether the equilibrium mixture contains more products or more reactants",
        "Le Chatelier's Principle":  "If a system at equilibrium is subjected to a change, the system will respond in the direction that opposes the change and restores a new equilibrium",
        "Equilibrium Constant (Kc)": "The ratio of product concentrations to reactant concentrations, each raised to the power of their stoichiometric coefficients, at equilibrium at a given temperature",
        "Kc >> 1":                   "Products are heavily favoured at equilibrium; reaction proceeds largely to completion",
        "Kc << 1":                   "Reactants are heavily favoured at equilibrium; very little product present at equilibrium",
        "Homogeneous Equilibrium":   "Equilibrium where all species are in the same phase (e.g. all aqueous or all gaseous)",
        "Heterogeneous Equilibrium": "Equilibrium where species are in different phases; pure solids and liquids are omitted from the Kc expression",
        "Yield":                     "The percentage of reactant converted to product; distinct from rate — high yield requires equilibrium to favour products",
        "Compromise Conditions":     "Industrial reaction conditions chosen to balance acceptable yield with acceptable rate, neither optimised individually"
    },

