        application: "When steam at 100°C contacts skin, it first condenses to liquid water at 100°C — releasing the latent heat of vaporisation of water (L_v = 2,260,000 J/kg = 2,260 J/g). Only then does the liquid water cool from 100°C to body temperature (37°C), releasing a further Q = mcΔT = 1 × 4,200 × 63 = 264,600 J/kg = 265 J/g. The total energy released by 1 g of steam reaching body temperature = 2,260 + 265 = 2,525 J/g. Liquid water at 100°C releases only 265 J/g on cooling to body temperature. Steam therefore deposits roughly 9.5 times more energy per gram into tissue — explaining the far greater tissue damage.",
        question: "Calculate the total energy released when 5 g of steam at 100°C cools to 37°C. (L_v = 2,260 J/g; c_water = 4.2 J/g°C)",
