        question: "At altitude, food takes longer to cook in boiling water despite the water boiling. Use particle theory to explain why lowering the boiling point reduces cooking speed.",
        answer: "Cooking involves chemical reactions (protein denaturation, starch gelatinisation) that have activation energy requirements — they occur faster at higher temperatures. When water boils at 70°C instead of 100°C, the thermal energy available to food molecules is lower — fewer food molecules have sufficient kinetic energy to overcome the activation energy of cooking reactions per unit time — so cooking rates decrease. The food is not receiving less heat; it is receiving heat at a lower temperature, which is chemically less effective.",
        extension: "This is an application of the Arrhenius equation principle: reaction rate increases exponentially with temperature. A 10°C decrease in cooking temperature can roughly halve the reaction rate. The 30°C difference at altitude (70°C vs 100°C) can reduce cooking rates by a factor of 8 or more for some reactions — explaining why food at altitude can take 3–4× as long to cook as at sea level."
