        application: "Inside the fridge (evaporator coils): refrigerant liquid evaporates at low pressure. Evaporation is endothermic — the refrigerant absorbs latent heat of vaporisation from the food and air inside the fridge, taking energy from the surroundings. At the particle level: the most energetic refrigerant molecules escape into the vapour phase, reducing the mean kinetic energy of the remaining liquid — the surroundings (food, air) transfer energy to maintain the refrigerant temperature, so they cool down. Outside the fridge (condenser coils): the refrigerant vapour is compressed and condenses back to liquid. Condensation is exothermic — latent heat of vaporisation is released to the surroundings outside the fridge. Net result: heat is transferred from inside to outside the fridge.",
