        answer: "The refrigerator simply transfers heat from one place to another — it does not destroy heat. With the door open, heat is removed from room air at the evaporator (inside) and deposited back into the same room at the condenser (outside, at the back). Net heat added to the room = electrical energy consumed by the compressor motor. The room temperature therefore rises slightly rather than falling.",
        extension: "Heat pumps use the same refrigeration cycle in reverse — they extract heat from cold outdoor air (evaporation) and deposit it inside a building (condensation). This is thermodynamically much more efficient than direct electrical heating: for every 1 kJ of electrical energy consumed, a heat pump can deliver 3–4 kJ of heat to the building. The coefficient of performance (COP) of a heat pump can exceed 3, making it far more energy-efficient than resistive heating."
