            "A chiral molecule is non-superimposable on its mirror image; requires at least one stereocentre (usually four different groups on C)",
            "Enantiomers are mirror images; identical physical properties except optical rotation and reactivity with chiral environments",
            "R/S (CIP system) describes absolute configuration; (+)/(-) describes optical rotation — no direct correlation",
            "Diastereomers differ at one or more but not all stereocentres; have different physical properties → can be separated",
            "Meso compounds have stereocentres but are achiral due to internal plane of symmetry",
            "SN2 gives inversion; SN1 gives racemisation; E2 requires anti-periplanar geometry → controls alkene geometry",
            "Conformational analysis: chair is the most stable cyclohexane conformation; substituents prefer equatorial positions",
            "Biological systems are highly stereospecific: enzymes discriminate between enantiomers and even enantiotopic groups",
            "Drug stereochemistry is critical: enantiomers can have very different — even opposite — biological activities"
